This Double Door floor shelf has an adjustable shelf hid behind the door panels. The sleek solid double doors on this floor cabinet are detailed in design and give a little more to the eye appeal. The Contempoary Country Line has many different styles, pieces, and colors to choose from. They are all ready to assemble, with all pieces being easy to assemble in minutes (simple instructions are included). Assembly instructions include 1-minute video links where assistance may be needed. The quality materials used along with a clean contemporary appeal will adorn any décor` for many years. All pieces of the Contemporary Country Collection are sold separately and available in a variety of colors.

reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Works perfectly as additional storage in my bathroom
reviews.reviewText: My current bathroom has a large empty space under the mirror/sink counter. I was looking for something to blend in with the white cabinet I have in my bathroom and this worked perfectly. It fits under the bathroom counter and almost matches my current white cabinet, including the hardware. It was pretty easy to put together, just me, but it would have gone quicker with a second person helping. I laid out all of the pieces prior to putting it together to make sure I had everything I needed before proceeding.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 28, 2020
reviews.reviewTitle: 3.0 out of 5 stars Functional but not high quality - as expected.
reviews.reviewText: For those who want to use this to store cookware and then complain that it’s too small...don’t. Read the dimensions for goodness sake! We bought this for a 1/2 bath to store extra TP, hand towels, soap, etc., works well for that purpose. But you do get what you pay for.The reason I give it 3-stars is because the tolerances of dowels and some other hardware to their respective holes do not align, at all. Either our dowels were far too narrow or the holes far too wide. Further, as the dowels are used to hold the bottom, front base trim in place to the sides and bottom of the cabinet, that piece would leave about a 1/2 gap between bottom of cabinet and top of trim. I used wood glue to fill the holes and then clamped it in place in effort to correct but after a few seconds the dowels popped up through the cabinet and the laminate finished broke away in about the circumference of a silver dollar. So it seems the holes were not just too wide but also too shallow (not deep enough). I then used a small piece of white paper and small piece of white duct tape to cover it up.No sense in returning it, even though I should. I’ll use it knowing that it’s not a quality piece of furniture meant to impress guests, it’s functional and temporary in the greater scheme of things.
